  "prompt": "What type of grapes are used to make wine?",
  "response": "A wide variety of grape types, known as varieties or cultivars, are used to make wine. These grapes fall into two main categories: **Vitis vinifera** (the European species) and hybrids or other species like **Vitis labrusca** (used for some American wines). Here\u2019s an overview of the most common grape types used in winemaking:\n\n### Red Wine Grapes:\n1. **Cabernet Sauvignon** - Full-bodied, with flavors of blackcurrant, cedar, and spice.\n2. **Merlot** - Softer than Cabernet, with plum, cherry, and herbal notes.\n3. **Pinot Noir** - Light to medium-bodied, with red fruit, earth, and mushroom flavors.\n4. **Syrah/Shiraz** - Bold and spicy, with dark fruit and pepper notes.\n5. **Zinfandel** - Known for jammy, fruit-forward flavors and high alcohol.\n6. **Sangiovese** - The main grape in Chianti, with cherry, tomato, and earthy tones.\n7. **Malbec** - Dark and fruity, often associated with Argentina.\n8. **Tempranillo** - The backbone of Rioja, with red fruit and leather flavors.\n\n### White Wine Grapes:\n1. **Chardonnay** - Versatile, ranging from buttery and oaky to crisp and mineral.\n2. **Sauvignon Blanc** - Crisp and aromatic, with citrus, grass, and green apple notes.\n3. **Riesling** - Can be dry to sweet, with floral, citrus, and stone fruit flavors.\n4. **Pinot Grigio/Pinot Gris** - Light and crisp (Pinot Grigio) or richer and spicier (Pinot Gris).\n5. **Chenin Blanc** - Versatile, with flavors of apple, pear, and honey.\n6. **Gew\u00fcrztraminer** - Aromatic, with lychee, rose, and spice notes.\n7. **Viognier** - Rich and floral, with peach and apricot flavors.\n\n### Other Notable Grapes:\n1. **Grenache** - Used in red blends, with red fruit and spice flavors.\n2. **Nebbiolo** - The grape behind Barolo and Barbaresco, with high tannins and floral notes.\n3. **Carm\u00e9n\u00e8re** - A Chilean specialty, with red fruit and herbal notes.\n4. **Albari\u00f1o** - A crisp white grape from Spain, with citrus and stone fruit flavors.\n5. **Moscato/Muscat** - Sweet and aromatic, often used in sparkling wines.\n\n### Hybrid Grapes:\n1. **Concord** - Used in some American wines, known for its bold, grapey flavor.\n2. **Vidal Blanc** - Often used for ice wine and dry whites.\n\nThe choice of grape depends on the region, climate, and the style of wine the winemaker aims to produce. Each grape imparts unique characteristics to the wine, from flavor and aroma to tannin and acidity levels.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
